<div class="comment-wrapper"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment"><div class="avatar"><img src="https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d53b7c5f9b5f5557b9082face9b632a0?s=50"></div><header><strong>Passing an optional first argument to sequence(first:next:)</strong> from <string>Dave Abrahams</string> &lt;dabrahams at apple.com&gt;<p>September  1, 2016 at 03:00:00pm</p></header><div class="content"><p>on Mon Aug 29 2016, Tim Vermeulen &lt;swift-evolution at swift.org&gt; wrote:<br></p><p>&gt; The intent of my function wasnâ€™t very clear, but it was supposed to<br>&gt; return a sequence that contains *all* consecutive pairs, i.e. (0 ..&lt;<br>&gt; 4).pairs would result in [(0, 1), (1, 2), (2, 3)].<br></p><p>extension Sequence {<br>  typealias Element = Iterator.Element<br>  <br>  /// All adjacent pairs of elements, in order.<br>  var allAdjacentPairs: UnfoldSequence&lt;(Element, Element), (i: Iterator, e: Element?)&gt; {<br>    var i = makeIterator()<br>    let e = i.next()<br>    <br>    return sequence(state: (i, e)) {<br>      (s: inout (i: Iterator, e: Element?))-&gt;(Element, Element)? in<br>      let e = s.i.next()<br>      defer { s.e = e }<br>      return e.map { (s.e!, $0) }<br>    }<br>  }<br>}<br></p><p>for j in 0..&lt;10 {<br>  print(Array((0..&lt;j).allAdjacentPairs))<br>}<br></p><p><br>-- <br>-Dave<br></p></div></li></ul></div>    </main>
